[normal]12)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As part of the stage 2 transfer process, a revised governance structure 
[normal]has been agreed 
[normal]with the Chief Constable 
[normal]which will see 
[normal]decisions being taken at a Joint Management Board.  The new governance arrangements will reduce bureaucracy and duplication
[normal] and 
[normal]enable closer joint working between 
[normal]my office 
[normal]and the Constabulary
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The role of the Commissioner in budget and precept setting[bold]&#xa0;[bold]13)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the current economic climate, a primary consideration for all Police and Crime Commissioners is how to balance the books against a backdrop of reducing financial resources, whilst seeking to maintain and improve services to the public.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]14)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In setting the budget for 2013/14, I had a shortfall of £8m compared to the budget for the previous year.  I proposed to raise the council tax precept by 1.99% to £153
[normal] for a Band D property
[normal], for the year 2013/14 and following extensive consultation this was supported by over 80% of the public surveyed. 
[normal]The public saw t
[normal]his increase of £3
[normal] per annum
[normal], or 6p per week, as a small price to pay
[normal] to maintain policing services in Cheshire
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] This rise in precept was supported by the Police and Crime Panel and raised £1.2 million to help meet the shortfall.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I am now in the process of considering the budget options for 2014/15.  A revised medium term financial strategy for 2014-18 has recently been approved and, following the root and branch review, I am confident Cheshire is on track to meet the required savings over this period.  Consultation has been taking place with the public and people have been asked whether they would be happy to pay another increase in the policing pa
[normal]rt of the council tax. Out of 1084
[normal] responses to date, 
[normal]7
[normal]5
[normal]%
[normal] of people said they would be prepared to pay a similar increase to last year. However, I am aware that people across the board are struggling, as the economy comes out of the recession. Taking all the above into consideration, I
[normal] a
[normal]m minded not to increase the council tax precept for policing next year. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effectiveness of Commissioner’s in promoting local policing priorities[bold]&#xa0;[bold]16)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A key role of Police and Crime Commissioners is to consult the public on their local priorities for policing to inform the objectives
[normal] contained 
[normal]within the Police and Crime Plan.  During my election campaign, I listened extensively to the views of the public and took this into account when developing my first Police and Crime Plan.  I am committed to ongoing consultation with the public and recently launched a ‘Victim
[normal]’
[normal]s Voice’ campaign to find what victims experience and what they expect from the police, victim support organisations and the criminal justice system
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]This will 
[normal]inform my decisions when I become responsible for commissioning some elements of victims services next year.  My office has also held focus groups with 
[normal]many different victims of crime
[normal] to understand their views on policing including: survivors of domestic abuse
[normal], people with mental health needs and people from the lesbian, gay, bi-sexual and transgender communities and faith groups.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are over 1 million people living in Cheshire, and 238,000 of them are under the age of 18.
[normal] 
[normal] I have appointed a Youth Ambassador to represent their views following consultation with young people about what they wanted from this role.  The Youth Ambassador has already gathered the views of over 1000 young people about personal safety, crime and policing and has been working with a myriad of organisations to provide advice and 
[normal]understand young people’s views
[normal]. 
[normal] The information obtained will be used to influence my Police and Crime Plan and future policing strategies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]18)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to be accessible to the people of Cheshire, I hold regular surgeries through the County and I have launched the Cheshire Crime Fighter App which enables local people to interact with the Constabulary.    A Crime Prevention Fund has also been launched which allows people to apply for funding to support community projects or initiatives. Since July, I’ve received 40 applications and granted over £58,000. All of the projects aim to improve people’s lives in their local area, by providing services or diversionary activities to reduce crime and anti-social behaviour.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Progress on establishing collaboration agreements with other commissioners, policing organisations and partners[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]19)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Greater collaboration will be essential to 
[normal]ensure the police service can provide the best possible service to the public.  T
[normal]he pace of change on collaboration 
[normal]is currently 
[normal]too slow
[normal] and 
[normal]I believe Commissioners must start driving this agenda now and look beyond regional collaborations which have prevailed in the past.  A good example of looking beyond region
[normal]al boundaries is the successful, innovative 
[normal]collaboration between Cheshire and Northamptonshire to deliver back office support functions whilst reducing costs.
[normal]  In Cheshire, the Constabulary and I are also working with neighbouring forces to explore opportunities for collaboration in respect of both operational policing and back office support functions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I am a member of the Strategic Police Procurement Board which is working to drive greater collaboration and efficiencies from police procurement practices.  I have also recently met representatives from the Fire &amp; Rescue Service and Ambulance Service to discuss collaboration opportunities between the three services.  Initial discussions have been positive and I am keen that we work together to deliver savings from better joined up working which can be reinvested on the front line.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Transparency of and reporting by Commissioners to date[bold]&#xa0;[bold]21)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In order to be accountable to the public, the decisions and performance of Commissioners must be visible and transparent.  I have strived to ensure that I am open and to demonstrate a high level of transparency.  Since taking up office, agenda papers for Decision Meetings and the notes of these meetings have been published on my website, providing details of significant decisions which have been taken.  Registers of interests and expense claims for myself and the 
[normal]Deputy Commissioner are also readily available on the website.   The Office of the Police and Crime Commissioner for Cheshire is able to demonstrate a high level of compliance with the statutory requirements to publish specified information.  
